"Colyton, Chumleigh, Devonshire, England, United Kingdom":"Colyton, Devon, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","England":"Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1494–10 August 1590":"1494–10 August 1590","1494–1590":"1494–1590","1490–1539":"1490–1539","1490–1590":"1490–1590","1511–1572":"1511–1572","1452–1507":"1452–1507","1464–1509":"1464–1509","1484":"1484","1572":"1572","1494":"1494","1571":"1571","abt 1572":"about 1572","1590":"1590","1490":"1490","1569":"1569","1558":"1558","10 August 1590":"10 August 1590","1511":"1511","1464":"1464","1452":"1452","1509":"1509","1507":"1507","15 Oct 1539":"15 October 1539","1539":"1539","1549":"1549","Rawkerayne, Devon{shire}, England":"Devon, England","Colyton, Devon, England":"Colyton, Devon, England","Wiltshire, England":"Wiltshire, England, United Kingdom","Colyton, , Devon, England":"Colyton, Devon, England, United Kingdom","Buckinghamshire, England":"Buckinghamshire, England, United Kingdom","Colyton, Chumleigh, Devonshire, England, United Kingdom":"Colyton, Devon, England, United Kingdom","England":"England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Tregoz","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Cornish (Cornwall and Devon): habitational name from Treago in Crantock (Cornwall). The placename derives from Middle Cornish <i>tre</i> ‘estate, farmstead’ + uncertain final element.","Altered form of French   Tricot   or of some other similar (like-sounding) surname. It was reportedly brought to North America from England. Today it is found mainly in PA and OH. Compare   Trago  .","History: This surname (see 2 above) is listed in the (US) National Huguenot Society's register of qualified Huguenot ancestors and also in the similar register of the Huguenot Society of America."],"variants":[{"name":"Tricot","meanings":["(2010: NA)","French:","nickname from a diminutive of <i>trique</i> ‘cudgel’."]},{"name":"Trago","meanings":["Variant of   Trego  , a surname of Cornish and French origin. In the US, it is found mainly in PA and OH."]}]},{"name":"Agnes","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Latinized version of the Greek name <i>Hagnē</i>, from the feminine form of the adjective <i>hagnos</i> ‘pure, holy’. This was the name of a young Roman virgin martyred in the persecutions instigated by the Roman emperor Diocletian in   ad  303 . She became a very popular saint in the Middle Ages. Her name was early associated with Latin <i>agnus</i> ‘lamb’, leading to the consistent dropping of the initial <i>H-</i> and to her representation in art accompanied by a lamb. The colloquial form <i>Annes</i> led to some confusion with <i>Ann(e)</i> in earlier centuries. Frequent in the medieval period, the name was revived in the 19th century, and has been especially popular in Scotland.  See also  Annis ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705201,"age":55,"year":"1549","julianDay":2286821,"title":"Book of Common Prayer","description":"Book of Common Prayer, a product of the English Reformation, was published in 1549 for assistance in the administration of the sacraments and other rites and ceremonies of the church according to the use of the Church of England. The book outlined morning, evening, and communion prayers and orders for baptism and marriage, thus making England a truly Protestant state.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Book_of_Common_Prayer","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Book of Common Prayer","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705202,"age":64,"year":"1558","julianDay":2290108,"title":"Act of Uniformity","description":"The Act of Uniformity was passed by the Parliament of England and required all people to go to church once a week. The consequence of not attending church was a fine of 12 pence, which was a considerable amount for a poor person.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705205,"age":75,"year":"1569","julianDay":2294126,"title":"State Lottery","description":"A State Lottery was recorded in 1569. The tickets were sold at St. Paul's Cathedral in London.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705206,"age":77,"year":"1571","julianDay":2294856,"title":"The Royal Exchange is Organized","description":"The Royal Exchange was organized in January 1571 by Sir Thomas Gresham. Gresham is known as the father of English banking.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Agnes Tregoz was born in 1494, in Devon, England, her father, Thomas Tregoys Tregoz, was 43 and her mother, Agnes Stewart, was 30. She died on 10 August 1590, in Colyton, Devon, England, at the age of 96."},"et":{"1494–10 August 1590":"1494–10. august 1590","1494–1590":"1494–1590","1490–1539":"1490–1539","1490–1590":"1490–1590","1511–1572":"1511–1572","1452–1507":"1452–1507","1464–1509":"1464–1509","1484":"1484","1572":"1572","1494":"1494","1571":"1571","abt 1572":"umbes 1572","1590":"1590","1490":"1490","1569":"1569","1558":"1558","10 August 1590":"10. august 1590","1511":"1511","1464":"1464","1452":"1452","1509":"1509","1507":"1507","15 Oct 1539":"15. oktoober 1539","1539":"1539","1549":"1549","Rawkerayne, Devon{shire}, England":"Devon, England","Colyton, Devon, England":"Colyton, Devon, England","Wiltshire, England":"Wiltshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Colyton, , Devon, England":"Colyton, Devon, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Buckinghamshire, England":"Buckinghamshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Colyton, Chumleigh, Devonshire, England, United Kingdom":"Colyton, Devon, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","England":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1494–10 August 1590":"1494–10. elokuuta 1590","1494–1590":"1494–1590","1490–1539":"1490–1539","1490–1590":"1490–1590","1511–1572":"1511–1572","1452–1507":"1452–1507","1464–1509":"1464–1509","1484":"1484","1572":"1572","1494":"1494","1571":"1571","abt 1572":"noin 1572","1590":"1590","1490":"1490","1569":"1569","1558":"1558","10 August 1590":"10. elokuuta 1590","1511":"1511","1464":"1464","1452":"1452","1509":"1509","1507":"